VALUES
(19, 104, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'He watereth the hills from his chambers:', 0, 40, 'greek', 'Understanding ''watereth''', 'מָשַׁק (mashaq, H4918) - to give drink, to water. This Hebrew term emphasizes the nurturing aspect of God''s relationship with creation, portraying Him as the provider of life-sustaining resources. The imagery of watering hills signifies God''s intentional care in ensuring that the natural world thrives, which can deepen our appreciation for His sustaining power.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H4918", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term used"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 104, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'the earth is satisfied with the fruit of thy works.', 41, 92, 'question', 'Reflecting on Creation''s Satisfaction', 'In what ways can we observe the earth''s satisfaction in relation to God''s provision? How does recognizing this satisfaction influence our understanding of stewardship and our role in caring for creation? This prompts a deeper exploration of our responsibilities as caretakers of the earth, reflecting on how we can align our actions with God''s purposes.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 104, 14, 14, 'kjv', 'He causeth the grass to grow for the cattle,', 0, 44, 'connection', 'Creation''s Provision', 'This phrase connects to Genesis 1:30, where God provides every green herb for food. Both passages showcase God''s care for creation, emphasizing His role as the sustainer of life. Understanding this connection highlights the divine order and intentionality behind creation, revealing God''s provision not just for humanity but for all living creatures.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 1:30", "description": "God''s provision of food for all creatures."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 104, 14, 14, 'kjv', 'for the cattle, and herb for the service of man:', 29, 77, 'theology', 'God''s Provision for All', 'This passage suggests a theological understanding of stewardship. Many scholars believe that God’s provision for both animals and humans reflects His desire for a harmonious ecosystem. It illustrates the interconnectedness of creation, where each element serves a purpose in fulfilling God’s design, calling humans to be responsible stewards of the earth and its resources.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 104, 14, 14, 'kjv', 'that he may bring forth food out of the earth;', 78, 124, 'question', 'Purpose of Provision', 'What does it mean for us to recognize that God brings forth food from the earth for our sustenance? How does this understanding influence our gratitude and responsibility towards food production and consumption? Reflecting on this can deepen our appreciation for God''s providence and call us to act with care for creation.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 104, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'wine that maketh glad the heart of man', 4, 42, 'connection', 'Joy in Wine', 'This phrase echoes Proverbs 3:13-15, which speaks of the value of wisdom, stating that she brings happiness and joy. The joy associated with wine here can be seen as a metaphor for the joy that wisdom brings to the heart. This connection emphasizes the blessings God provides for both physical and spiritual well-being.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Proverbs 3:13-15", "description": "Proverbs highlights the joy of wisdom, paralleling the joy of wine."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 104, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'oil to make his face to shine', 48, 77, 'theology', 'Symbol of Blessing', 'Oil in the ancient Near East is often viewed as a symbol of divine blessing and anointing. Many scholars believe this passage suggests that the blessings from God not only sustain life but also enhance one''s countenance, reflecting His favor and joy in the believer''s life. This theme of divine favor is prevalent throughout Scripture.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Explains the symbolic meaning of oil in biblical texts."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 104, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'bread which strengtheneth man’s heart', 83, 120, 'question', 'Spiritual Nourishment', 'How does the concept of bread as a source of strength reflect your understanding of Jesus as the ''Bread of Life''? In what ways does this metaphor challenge you to seek spiritual nourishment in your daily life?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 104, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'The trees of the Lord are full of sap;', 0, 38, 'theology', 'God''s Provision in Creation', 'This phrase reflects God''s active role in creation, emphasizing His sustenance of life. The trees symbolize not only physical provision but also spiritual nourishment, illustrating an overarching theme in Scripture where God continually provides for His creation. Many scholars believe this verse invites believers to recognize the interconnectedness of all life and God''s nurturing character.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 104, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'the cedars of Lebanon, which he hath planted;', 39, 84, 'connection', 'Symbolism of Cedars', 'The cedars of Lebanon are often referenced in Scripture as symbols of strength, beauty, and longevity. For example, in 1 Kings 6:15, Solomon used cedar wood for the temple, highlighting its significance. This connection matters because it underscores God''s intention to create enduring beauty and stability in His creation, reflecting His glory.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "1 Kings 6:15", "description": "Solomon''s use of cedar wood in the temple emphasizes the strength and beauty of God''s creation."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 104, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'The trees of the Lord are full of sap;', 0, 38, 'greek', 'Understanding ''sap''', 'The Hebrew word for ''sap'' used here is ''שֶׁמֶן'' (shemen, H8081) - oil, fat, or grease. This term not only refers to the physical nourishment of trees but can also symbolize the richness of God''s blessings. The imagery conveys a sense of vitality and abundance present in the natural world.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H8081", "description": "Strong''s number for ''shemen'', indicating its use in describing richness and nourishment."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 104, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'The trees of the Lord are full of sap;', 0, 38, 'question', 'Reflecting on God''s Care', 'What does it mean for us to recognize that ''the trees of the Lord are full of sap''? How might this understanding of God''s provision and care for creation influence our stewardship of the environment?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 104, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'Where the birds make their nests:', 0, 33, 'connection', 'Birds and Creation Care', 'This phrase echoes Jesus'' teaching in Matthew 6:26, where He points to the birds of the air and how God provides for them. The connection highlights God''s providence in creation and invites reflection on our relationship with the environment. It emphasizes that God''s care extends to all creatures, fostering a sense of responsibility toward creation.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Matthew 6:26", "description": "Jesus teaches about God''s provision for birds, parallel to the care in creation."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 104, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'as for the stork, the fir trees are her house.', 34, 80, 'theology', 'God''s Provision for All Creatures', 'This passage suggests that God provides specific habitats for different creatures, reflecting His wisdom in creation. Many scholars believe this illustrates a broader theological principle of God''s intimate involvement in the natural world and His provision for all living beings. It encourages believers to recognize God''s hand in the diversity of life.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 104, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'the stork, the fir trees are her house.', 41, 80, 'greek', 'Meaning of ''Stork''', 'חסידה (chasidah, H2623) - stork, a bird often associated with kindness and parental care. This term emphasizes the nurturing aspect of the stork, aligning with themes of protection and provision found throughout Scripture.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H2623", "description": "Strong''s Hebrew number for ''stork,'' highlighting its significance."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 104, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'Where the birds make their nests:', 0, 33, 'question', 'Reflecting on God''s Care', 'What does it mean for you to know that God provides homes for even the smallest of creatures, like birds? How does this understanding shape your view of God''s provision in your own life?', 'heart.text.square', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 104, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'The high hills are a refuge for the wild goats;', 0, 47, 'connection', 'Refuge in Nature', 'This imagery of high hills as a refuge resonates with Psalm 61:3, which states, ''For you have been my refuge, a strong tower against the enemy.'' Both passages highlight God’s provision and safety found in natural elements, suggesting that creation itself reflects divine care and protection.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 61:3", "description": "Psalm 61 emphasizes God as a refuge."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 104, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'The high hills are a refuge for the wild goats;', 0, 47, 'theology', 'God''s Provision', 'This verse suggests a theological principle regarding God’s provision for His creation. Many scholars believe that the ''refuge'' provided for the wild goats illustrates God''s care and design in nature, showing that He not only creates but sustains life through the environments He provides.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Henry discusses God''s care for all creatures."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 104, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'the rocks for the conies.', 52, 77, 'greek', 'Conies Explained', 'שָׁפָן (shapan, H8227) - cony, rock badger. The term refers to an animal that seeks shelter in rocky areas, emphasizing the concept of safety found in God’s creation. This highlights a theme of reliance on God for protection and survival in the natural world.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H8227", "description": "Strong''s number for conies in Hebrew."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 104, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'The high hills are a refuge for the wild goats;', 0, 47, 'question', 'Finding Refuge', 'In what ways do you seek refuge in God when facing life''s challenges? How does the metaphor of high hills and wild goats encourage you to trust in His protection during difficult times?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 104, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'He appointed the moon for seasons', 0, 33, 'connection', 'Celestial Appointments', 'This phrase connects to Genesis 1:14, where God creates lights in the sky to separate day from night and to mark seasons. The appointment of the moon and sun emphasizes God''s sovereignty over time and creation, reinforcing the idea that celestial bodies serve His purposes.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 1:14", "description": "God''s creation of celestial bodies to mark time and seasons."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 104, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'the sun knoweth his going down', 35, 65, 'theology', 'God''s Sovereignty in Nature', 'Many scholars believe this verse illustrates God''s control over natural cycles. The sun''s knowing its going down suggests a divine order in creation, reflecting the consistent rhythms established by God. This reinforces the Christian belief in God''s sovereignty over both creation and time, as articulated in the Westminster Confession of Faith.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Westminster Confession of Faith", "description": "A historic document summarizing Reformed theology."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 104, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'He appointed the moon for seasons', 0, 33, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Appointed''', 'מָנָה (manah, H4487) - to set, appoint, or arrange. This Hebrew term emphasizes God''s intentionality in creation. The use of ''appointed'' indicates a deliberate act of establishing the moon''s role in marking time, which reflects the order and purpose inherent in God''s creation.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H4487", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word meaning ''to appoint.''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 104, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'appointed the moon for seasons', 3, 33, 'question', 'Reflecting on Divine Order', 'What does it mean to you that God has appointed the moon for seasons in your life? How might this understanding of divine order influence your daily decisions and trust in God''s timing?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 104, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'Thou makest darkness, and it is night:', 0, 38, 'connection', 'Creation''s Order', 'This phrase connects to Genesis 1:5, where God distinguishes between light and darkness, naming the darkness ''Night.'' This highlights God''s sovereignty in creating and ordering the world. The presence of night is not merely a lack of light, but part of God''s intentional design for the rhythm of creation.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 1:5", "description": "God''s creation of light and darkness"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 104, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'wherein all the beasts of the forest do creep forth.', 39, 91, 'theology', 'God''s Provision for Creation', 'This passage suggests a theological understanding of God as the provider for all living creatures. Many scholars believe it reflects God''s ongoing care for creation, as the beasts emerge at night to fulfill their natural instincts. This can lead to reflections on how God''s provision extends to all aspects of life, nurturing and sustaining His creation.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 104, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'Thou makest darkness, and it is night:', 0, 38, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Darkness''', 'חֹשֶׁךְ (choshekh, H2822) - darkness. This Hebrew word conveys not just the absence of light, but a state of obscurity and mystery. It emphasizes the intentionality of God in creating both light and darkness, inviting contemplation on the spiritual implications of darkness in our lives.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H2822", "description": "Hebrew term for darkness"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 104, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'wherein all the beasts of the forest do creep forth.', 39, 91, 'question', 'Reflecting on Night''s Purpose', 'What does it mean for us to recognize that night is part of God''s creation? How might understanding the beasts'' behavior at night inform our view of God''s design and our role within it? Consider how the cycles of creation reflect deeper spiritual truths.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 104, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'The young lions roar after their prey, and seek their meat from God.', 0, 68, 'connection', 'Divine Provision in Creation', 'This verse connects to Matthew 6:26, which states, ''Look at the birds of the air; they do not sow or reap or store away in barns, and yet your heavenly Father feeds them.'' Both passages emphasize God''s provision for His creation, showcasing His care for all living beings, including young lions seeking their sustenance. This connection enriches our understanding of God''s continual involvement in the natural world.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Matthew 6:26", "description": "Jesus teaches about God''s provision for all creatures."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 104, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'seek their meat from God.', 43, 68, 'theology', 'God as Sustainer', 'This phrase suggests that all creatures depend on God for their sustenance, reflecting a key theological principle of divine providence. Many scholars believe this reveals not just God''s role as Creator but also as Sustainer, indicating that He continues to actively provide for His creation. This understanding encourages a view of God as intimately involved in the daily lives of all living beings.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "John Calvin''s Commentary on Psalms", "description": "Calvin discusses God''s providential care over nature."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 104, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'The young lions roar after their prey,', 0, 38, 'question', 'Understanding Spiritual Hunger', 'What does the imagery of young lions roaring for their prey reveal about our own spiritual hunger for God? Just as these lions seek their sustenance, how might we seek after God in our daily lives? Reflecting on this can deepen our understanding of our dependence on God for both physical and spiritual nourishment.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 104, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'roar after their prey, and seek their meat from God.', 16, 68, 'greek', 'Seeking Divine Sustenance', 'Hebrew: בָּקַשׁ (baqash, H1245) - to seek, search for, desire. This term implies a deep yearning and active pursuit, emphasizing that seeking God is not passive but an earnest endeavor. It highlights the intensity with which both animals and humans should approach their need for God''s provision.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H1245", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term used."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 104, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'The sun ariseth, they gather themselves together, and lay them down in their dens.', 0, 82, 'connection', 'Creation and Order', 'This verse connects to Genesis 1:14-19, where the creation of the sun and its purpose to govern day and night is established. Both passages emphasize the role of the sun in the divine order of creation, highlighting God''s authority over nature and the rhythm of life. This connection invites reflection on how God''s creation is intentional and purposeful.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 1:14-19", "description": "Describes the creation of the sun, moon, and stars."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 104, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'The sun ariseth, they gather themselves together, and lay them down in their dens.', 0, 82, 'theology', 'God''s Sovereignty in Nature', 'This passage suggests that God orchestrates the natural world, demonstrating His sovereignty. Many scholars believe this reflects the Biblical theme of divine provision, where God not only creates but also sustains life. The rhythm of day and night serves to remind believers of God''s control over creation and His provision for all creatures.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses God''s providence and order in creation."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 104, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'The sun ariseth, they gather themselves together, and lay them down in their dens.', 0, 82, 'question', 'Reflection on Daily Rhythm', 'How does the cycle of day and night in this verse reflect God''s design for rest and work in our lives? In what ways can we honor this rhythm in our daily routines, recognizing the importance of both labor and rest?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 104, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'The sun ariseth, they gather themselves together, and lay them down in their dens.', 0, 82, 'greek', 'Hebrew Insights', 'שמש (shemesh, H8121) - sun. This word signifies not only the physical sun but also represents light, warmth, and life. In Hebrew thought, the sun often symbolizes God''s presence and blessing, illuminating the connection between God''s creative power and the sustenance of life.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H8121", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word for sun."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 104, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'Man goeth forth unto his work', 0, 29, 'connection', 'Work in Creation', 'This phrase connects to Genesis 2:15, where God places Adam in the Garden of Eden to ''work it and keep it.'' This emphasizes the biblical view of work as a divine calling, reflecting God''s own creative activity. The idea of man performing labor is not merely a survival tactic but an integral part of God''s design for human life.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 2:15", "description": "God''s command for man to work in the garden"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 104, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'until the evening', 48, 65, 'theology', 'Work and Rest', 'Many scholars believe this phrase highlights the rhythm of work and rest established by God. The concept of evening symbolizes a time for reflection and rest after a day of labor, aligning with the Sabbath principle found in Exodus 20:8-11. This teaches that while work is essential, it must be balanced with rest, which is also a divine mandate.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Exodus 20:8-11", "description": "The command to observe the Sabbath and rest"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 104, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'goeth forth', 4, 15, 'greek', 'Movement and Purpose', 'יצא (yatza, H3318) - to go out, to come forth. This Hebrew term indicates purposeful movement, suggesting that human labor is an active engagement in the world. It carries the implication that work is not just a duty but a journey towards fulfilling God’s purpose.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H3318", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word for ''go out''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 104, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'Man goeth forth unto his work', 0, 29, 'question', 'Understanding Our Labor', 'In what ways does the idea of ''going forth'' to work reflect your daily responsibilities? How can viewing work as a divine calling change your approach to challenges faced in your vocation?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 104, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'O Lord, how manifold are thy works!', 0, 35, 'connection', 'Creation''s Diversity', 'This phrase echoes the sentiment of Genesis 1:31, where God sees all that He has made and declares it ''very good.'' The connection underscores the beauty and intentionality behind creation, reinforcing that God''s works are not only numerous but also diverse and purposeful. This appreciation of God''s creative power invites us to reflect on the intricacies of the world around us.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 1:31", "description": "God''s declaration of the goodness of His creation."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 104, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'in wisdom hast thou made them all:', 36, 70, 'greek', 'Wisdom in Creation', 'σοφία (sophia, G4678) - wisdom, insight. This term denotes not merely knowledge but the application of knowledge effectively. The use of ''wisdom'' in this context suggests that God''s creation is not random but rather a reflection of His intelligent design, inviting admiration and reverence for the Creator''s capabilities.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G4678", "description": "Strong''s number for the Greek term ''wisdom.''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 104, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'the earth is full of thy riches.', 71, 103, 'theology', 'God''s Abundance', 'This passage suggests that God''s creation is abundant and generous, reflecting His character as a provider. Many scholars believe that this abundance is not just material but also spiritual, inviting believers to recognize and steward the gifts of creation responsibly. The richness of the earth calls for gratitude and a deepened sense of responsibility towards environmental stewardship.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 104, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'O Lord, how manifold are thy works!', 0, 35, 'question', 'Reflecting on Creation', 'How does recognizing the manifold works of the Lord deepen your appreciation for the world around you? In what ways can you actively acknowledge and celebrate God''s creativity in your life?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 104, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'this great and wide sea', 6, 29, 'connection', 'Creation''s Majesty', 'The phrase ''this great and wide sea'' resonates with Genesis 1:10, where God calls the dry land ''Earth'' and the gathering of waters ''Seas.'' This connection emphasizes the grandeur of God''s creation and His sovereign authority over it. The sea, in its vastness, reflects the limitless nature of God''s creation, inspiring awe and reverence.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 1:10", "description": "God''s naming of the seas highlights His creative power."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 104, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'things creeping innumerable', 43, 70, 'theology', 'God''s Provision in Creation', 'This phrase suggests that God''s creation is teeming with life, which many scholars believe reflects God''s ongoing provision for His creatures. It reminds believers of the interconnectedness of all creation and God''s sustaining power over the natural world, highlighting the importance of stewardship as seen in Genesis 1:28.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 104, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'both small and great beasts', 72, 99, 'greek', 'The Diversity of Creation', 'בְּהֵמָה (behemah, H929) - beast, animal. This Hebrew term encompasses a wide range of creatures, both large and small, highlighting the diversity within creation. The inclusion of both ''small and great'' reminds us of God''s creativity in forming all life, regardless of size, underscoring that every creature has its place in the ecosystem.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H929", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word for beast."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 104, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'both small and great beasts', 72, 99, 'question', 'Reflecting on Diversity', 'How does recognizing ''both small and great beasts'' affect your understanding of God''s creation? In what ways can we appreciate and care for all aspects of the natural world, regardless of their size or perceived importance?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 104, 26, 26, 'kjv', 'There go the ships:', 0, 19, 'connection', 'Ships in Scripture', 'The mention of ships evokes connections to other passages like Jonah 1:3, where ships are involved in a narrative of flight and divine intervention. This highlights the contrast between human endeavors at sea and God''s sovereign control over creation. The imagery of ships can symbolize both human ambition and God''s overarching purpose in the world.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Jonah 1:3", "description": "Jonah''s journey on a ship illustrates God''s control over the sea."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 104, 26, 26, 'kjv', 'leviathan, whom thou hast made', 34, 64, 'theology', 'Creation and Sovereignty', 'The leviathan serves as a powerful symbol of God''s creative authority, reflecting the belief that all creatures, even those that seem chaotic or fearsome, are under His sovereign control. Many scholars believe this verse underscores the relationship between God as creator and creation itself, emphasizing His power and the order He instills in nature.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Henry discusses the significance of God''s sovereignty over all creation."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini');